  "id": 133135,
  "referenceId": 109189,
  "name": "2 Samuel 15:1–20:26",
  "localizedName": "2 Samuel 15:1–20:26",
  "content": [
    {
      "tiptap": {
        "type": "doc",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "Absalom continued to cause trouble in David’s family. He didn’t honour God’s choice of David as the king. Absalom wanted to make himself king while David was still alive. He hadn’t been chosen by God or anointed by a "
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "marks": [
                  {
                    "type": "resourceReference",
                    "attrs": {
                      "resourceId": "108416",
                      "resourceType": "BiblicaStudyNotesKeyTerms"
                    }
                  }
                ],
                "text": "prophet"
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": " to be king. But he convinced many Israelites to follow him."
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "He made plans to kill his father and he had sex with David’s "
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "marks": [
                  {
                    "type": "resourceReference",
                    "attrs": {
                      "resourceId": "108265",
                      "resourceType": "BiblicaStudyNotesKeyTerms"
                    }
                  }
                ],
                "text": "concubines"
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": ". This was a way to show that he had more authority in Jerusalem than David did. It also fulfilled part of Nathan’s "
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "marks": [
                  {
                    "type": "resourceReference",
                    "attrs": {
                      "resourceId": "108399",
                      "resourceType": "BiblicaStudyNotesKeyTerms"
                    }
                  }
                ],
                "text": "prophecy"
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": " against David for committing adultery and murder."
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "As David ran away from Absalom, he made careful plans. He received help from people who remained faithful to him. David also prayed ("
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "marks": [
                  {
                    "type": "resourceReference",
                    "attrs": {
                      "resourceId": "108227",
                      "resourceType": "BiblicaStudyNotesKeyTerms"
                    }
                  }
                ],
                "text": "prayer"
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": ") to God for help. David didn’t want to punish those who spoke against him. Instead he trusted God to provide the "
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "marks": [
                  {
                    "type": "resourceReference",
                    "attrs": {
                      "resourceId": "108379",
                      "resourceType": "BiblicaStudyNotesKeyTerms"
                    }
                  }
                ],
                "text": "covenant blessings"
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": " for him."
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "Even though Absalom had become David’s enemy, David didn’t celebrate when Absalom was killed. After that, David returned to Jerusalem to continue ruling as king."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  ],
